04388nam a22005535i 9780822389453DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223894537 a10.1515/97808223894532doi  a(DE-B1597)554207  a(OCoLC)1224279117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF2651.S257bW66 2009 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a306.20981/09042221 aWoodard, James P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Place in Politics :bSão Paulo, Brazil, from Seigneurial Republicanism to Regionalist Revolt /cJames P. Woodard. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (422 p.) :b4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Orthography of Brazilian Portuguese -- tIntroduction -- t1. São Paulo as a Developing Society -- t2. A Republic of Layers -- t3. War and the Health of the State -- t4. Knaves, Pedants, and Rebels -- t5. An Experiment in Democracy -- t6. Moments and Truths -- tConclusion and Epilogue Politics, Culture, and Class in the History of Twentieth-Century Brazil -- tGlossary of Portuguese Terms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA Place in Politics is a thorough reinterpretation of the politics and political culture of the Brazilian state of São Paulo between the 1890s and the 1930s. The world's foremost coffee-producing region from the outset of this period and home to more than six million people by 1930, São Paulo was an economic and demographic giant. In an era marked by political conflict and dramatic social and cultural change in Brazil, nowhere were the conflicts as intense or changes more dramatic than in São Paulo. The southeastern state was the site of the country's most important political developments, from the contested presidential campaign of 1909-10 to the massive military revolt of 1924. Drawing on a wide array of source materials, James P. Woodard analyzes these events and the republican political culture that informed them.Woodard's fine-grained political history proceeds chronologically from the final years of the nineteenth century, when São Paulo's leaders enjoyed political preeminence within the federal system codified by the Constitution of 1891, through the mass mobilization of 1931-32, in which São Paulo's people marched, rioted, and eventually took up arms against the national government in what was to be Brazil's last great regionalist revolt. In taking to the streets in the name of their state, constitutionalism, and the "civilization" that they identified with both, the people of São Paulo were at once expressing their allegiance to elements of a regionally distinct political culture and converging on a broader, more participatory public sphere that had arisen amid the political conflicts of the preceding decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aPolitical culturezBrazilzSão PauloxHistory. 0aRegionalismzBrazilzSão PauloxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389453zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822389453.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles